  "body": " Homework 7  Due Wednesday, October 29    [Chapter 5, starting p.150]: 1.1 (a), (b)   Note about 1.1(b): For this particular angle, the rotation could be visualized geometrically. However, I would like you to follow the procedure of finding the matrix that we described in class: Find an orthonormal basis with matrix first using the Gram-Schmidt algorithm, and then use the change of basis formula.     [Chapter 6, starting p.188]: 3.2, 3.6(ab)     [Problem A] Let denote a linear operator and let be an ortonormal basis of . Let denote the matrix of with respect to the basis (considered on both the domain and codomain).   Prove that is orthogonal if and only if is an orthogonal matrix.    Assume . Prove that is a rotation if and only if .       For (a), use Propositions 5.1.14 and 4.2.13. For (b), you may use Euler's theorem as well.      [Problem B] Let . Describe geometrically the operator .      [Problem C] Let and let be two rotations in . Show that there exists and an angle such that the composition is a rotation . (In short: composition of two rotations in is a rotation. This is a trivial statement in , but it is not as trivial in when we rotate around different pole vectors.)    Use Euler's theorem to translate into a statement about matrices.      [Problem D] Let with . Prove that has an eigenvalue .    Mimic, with adjustments as needed, the proof of Lemma 5.1.29      [Problem E] Euler's theorem describes all matrices in with determinant as being rotation matrices. We can understand thus the operators given by such matrices in a geometric manner: rotate in a plane perpendicular to some pole vector (that is an eigenvector for the matrix), leaving the pole vector unchanged.  If with , can you describe geometrically (in a somewhat similar manner) the operators given by these matrices? How do these operators act on points in ?      [Problem F] Let , and denote isometries in such that:     is a reflection in a line    is a rotation of angle (not necessarily though the origin)     is a reflection in a line     Prove that the composition is a rotation or a translation.    Note that rotations and translations are precisely the isometries of that are orientation preserving. Remember that isometries form a group and think about how one can decide orientation preserving or reversing.      [Problem G] Let denote a rotation of angle in the plane, about the point . Find a vector such that and then write an explicit formula for for any .      [Problem H] Working in the group of all translations in (it is a group with respect to composition): Note that, if is a nonzero vector in , then because has infinite order. (Recall that is the cyclic group generated by an element of infinite order. It is isomorphic to .)  Now prove: If and are two linearly independent vectors in , then (or if you want.) Make sure to emphasize in your proof how the hypothesis that are linearly independent is used.    Use the Product Proposition. Note that .      [Problem F] Suppose is a function that preserves dot products. In other words, for all , we have . (To simplify notation we write instead of .) Using only basic properties of dot product (such as the distributive law) and the definition of length:    Prove that for all , we have .    Prove that for all , we have .    Prove that , by taking in part (b).      Note: this problem addresses the implication in Theorem 6.2.3.     "
